			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Designing Variability Modeling Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/KrzysztofCzarnecki.html">Krzysztof Czarnecki</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_12">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_12</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> The work targets variability modeling and product line engineering as the primary concern.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It discusses how to design a variability modeling language and its constructs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> A variability modeling language is treated as a DSL for expressing variation points and constraints.
</li></ul></li></ul>
